Certainly, Jack! If you want to express the height of a textarea column in percentage relative to its container, you can use the CSS `height` property with a percentage value. Here's an example of how you can achieve this in a Flask application using HTML and a bit of CSS:

```python
from flask import Flask, render_template

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def index():
    return render_template('index.html')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
```

Now, create a folder named `templates` in your project directory, and inside that folder, create a file named `index.html`. Here's the content:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Textarea in Percentage</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }

        .container {
            width: 50%;
        }

        textarea {
            width: 100%;
            height: 30%; /* You can adjust this percentage as needed */
            resize: none;
        }

        button {
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <textarea id="myTextarea"></textarea>
        <button onclick="getText()">Get Text</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        function getText() {
            var text = document.getElementById("myTextarea").value;
            alert("Textarea Content: " + text);
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `height` property of the textarea is set to 30%, but you can adjust this value based on your preference. The container is set to 50% of the width for demonstration purposes.

